    "recap_headline": "Kent State University",
    "recap_text": "HARTFORD, Conn.\n\u2014 In a game that went back and forth until the final out, the Kent State Golden Flashes held on to defeat Massachusetts 9-8 on Sunday at DiBenedetto Stadium, completing their fourth sweep of the season and improving to 18-4 overall and 8-1 in MAC play. The 18-4 start is the best in the program since 1983, when the Flashes opened 19-3.\nKent State struck early and often, plating four runs in the second inning to set the tone.\nBrady Marshall\nand\nAlejandro Covas\ndrew back-to-back walks, and after\nLuke Matthews\nlaid down a sacrifice bunt to move both runners up,\nMicah Rienstra-Kiracofe\ndoubled to deep left field to clear the bases and make it 2-0.\nSawyer Solitaria\nthen followed with a two-run home run to left field to push the lead to 4-0. Massachusetts answered with a Will Briggs solo shot in the bottom half, and Briggs homered again in the fourth to cut the deficit to 4-2, but the Flashes were far from done.\nKent State broke the game open again in the fifth with another four-run outburst.\nRipken Reese\nled off with a solo home run to left, and the Flashes kept right on rolling.\nNolan Belcher\ndoubled and scored on an\nAlejandro Covas\nRBI single, Matthews doubled home another run, and Rienstra-Kiracofe reached on a\u00a0fielder's\u00a0choice to plate Covas and push the lead to 8-2. It looked as though the Flashes were in command.\nMassachusetts had other ideas. The Minutemen chipped away with two runs in the seventh, erupted for three more in the eighth on a Ty Fox RBI single, a Willi Marc RBI single, and a Ty Fox RBI double to make it a one-run game at 8-7 heading to the ninth.\nThe Flashes got an insurance run in the ninth when\nMax Humphrey\ndoubled and scored on a\nBrady Marshall\nsacrifice fly to make it 9-7. It proved necessary.\nEvan Holewinski\ncame on to close in the ninth, and after retiring the first batter, he gave up\u00a0Briggs'\u00a0third home run of the game to make it 9-8. But Holewinski buckled down, striking out the final two batters to slam the door and earn his third save of the season.\nBen Rabatin\nearned the win to improve to 3-0, going six innings and striking out seven while allowing just two runs. Rienstra-Kiracofe finished 1-for-4 with two RBI, while Reese went 1-for-3 with a home run, two RBI, and two walks. Solitaria's two-run shot in the second gave him eight home runs on the season. The Flashes issued 13 walks on the afternoon and did not commit an error, playing a clean game defensively despite the bullpen's late-inning struggles.\nThe Flashes return home to host Pittsburgh on\u00a0Tuesday, March 24, at 3 p.m.\u00a0at Schoonover Stadium.\n---\nBe The Difference, Support the Baseball Excellence Fund\nSupport the baseball program today by donating to the Baseball Excellence Fund by\nclicking here.\nFollow Kent State Baseball\nFor complete coverage of Kent State Baseball, download the official Kent State Golden Flashes app (\niOS\n,\nAndroid\n) and follow the Golden Flashes on social media on\nX\n,\nInstagram\n, and\nFacebook\nfor news and updates.",
